Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you donâ€™t have symptoms.

Airports in the Cayman Islands are closed to all inbound and outbound international passenger flights until further notice.
A flight has been chartered by the Cayman Islands Government to return people to the UK from the Cayman Islands and Turks and Caicos. This flight will depart from Grand Cayman to London Heathrow on Wednesday 29 April. For further information see, Return to the UK.
Cargo flights, couriers and air ambulance services continue to operate as usual. Travel helplines are available to offer advice and assistance to those with an urgent or compassionate need to travel.
In the Cayman Islands call +1 345 244 3333 or email emergencytravel@gov.ky.
In the UK please contact the Cayman Islands Office in the UK on 0207 491 7772 or info@cigouk.ky
Inter-Island flights will continue; however, flights from Grand Cayman into Cayman Brac and Little Cayman will be restricted to residents and essential persons, for example, medical staff.
The Cayman Islands has implemented shelter in place regulations which restricts travel to public places (supermarkets, banks etc.) between 5am and 7pm and restricts all movement between 7pm and 5am except for essential workers.
There is a ban on public meetings and gatherings of two people or more until further notice. This ban excludes premises such as hospitals, pharmacies and supermarkets. The fine for breaching the ban on public gatherings is CI$1,000 or up to six months imprisonment.
Workplaces - unless they have been designated as essential public places or provide essential services - are closed.
Restaurants are open for curbside pick-up, drive-through delivery only. Bars, spas, gyms, hairdressers, public and private strata swimming pools are also closed. The bus service has been suspended and taxis are limited to two passengers only.
Educational facilities are closed until 27 April 2020.
On Monday 16 March the Cayman Islands Government imposed a ban on cruise ships docking in the Cayman Islands for 60 days.
Further information
More information is available on the Cayman Islands website.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
